history.content:
How comfortable are you working in C and debugging C code with GDB? Can you draw the C memory layout (i.e. arrange these from lowest to highest address: code, heap, static, stack)? Can you list the instructions (in assembly) that get executed when a function is called?

These are the main 61C concepts relevant in 161, so if you have prior experience, you should be fine. If none of that makes sense to you, you're probably going to have to invest more time in the first few weeks of 161. Only the first few weeks require 61C though, so afterwards you can finish the class without any 61C knowledge.

As for studying ahead, it depends on what you have prior experience in. If you don't have any prior experience, I'd highly recommend going through the 61C lectures/assignments up until lecture 10 at least, and then looking through the 61C review stuff on the 161 website.

children.subject:
That answer sounds good to me! You certainly don't need to get those questions perfectly correct to do well in 161 - we'll spend some time in class reviewing all the concepts you need and adapting from RISC-V to x86.

IMO, the prerequisite bar for taking 161 without 61C is a little higher than the bar for taking 161 with 61C. If you've taken 61C, even if you didn't do amazingly, we at least know that you've seen these concepts at least once, so it's easier to review the concepts and catch you back up on the relevant parts. However, if you haven't taken 61C, and you don't have any prior experience, you're going to be seeing a lot of these concepts for the first time (and at a really quick pace), so it'll take more time investment at the beginning of the semester to catch up and stay on track.

<md>> Can you list the instructions (in assembly) that get executed when a function is called?

I think generally you would store all registers on the stack then unconditionally branch (may be called a jmp?) to the function definition (and linking the next instruction address to a return address register so you know where to return to and restore aka "load" registers from)? I think 161 uses x86 not RISC so it may be different names: i think Base pointer/Stack Pointer/Instruction Pointer is used instead of program counter in x86?

I struggled a lot in CS 61C (was consistently below mean on exams and projects) and remember very little of the small details, do you have any resources/tips to do well in 161 this summer especially if i didn't get the above question correct? I want to do well in 161 summer</md>
